postcontent:
Utah CFP Oregon CHL Concealed Carry Class

Friday, August 22, 2014 7:00 PM

Honey Toast Cafe, 12520 SW Farmington Road, Beaverton, OR 97005

Class cost is $65. Save $5 by pre-registering online!

Pre-Register Online: http://www.keepcalmandcarry.net/utah-cfp-oregon-chl-concealed-carry-class-1-9-2014-Registration

This class covers everything you need to get your Oregon Concealed Handgun License and your Utah Concealed Firearms Permit. 

Our course exceeds all firearms safety training exceeds the requirements to obtain your Utah CFP, pursuant to Utah Code Title 53 Chapter 5 Section 704, and your Oregon CHL pursuant to ORS 166.291(f)(G). 

Our process starts with issuing you a packet of information, an application for your permit, and fingerprint cards that you will need. We will do your fingerprinting, take your passport photo and make copies of your driver's license before class starts. We do this so that upon completion of this class, you will have a complete packet which you can submit to Utah BCI (Bureau of Criminal Identification) with your payment. You will also have all the information you need to obtain your Oregon CHL from your local Sheriff's department. 

Subjects covered are: Basic Handgun Safety, Tactical Issues, Concealed Carry Firearm selection tips, Ammunition, Holsters, Gun Free Zones, Reciprocity, Cleaning, Storage, Firearm Transport, Justifiable Force, Criminal and Civil liability, How to interact with Law Enforcement, and how to apply for your Permit. 

After attending this class you will have a fundamental understanding about handgun safety and the rights and responsibilities and laws associated with the carrying of a concealed Handgun in multiple states. 

This is NOT a live firing class. Do NOT bring a firearm with you to the class. 

Even though the class time is only scheduled to be 2 1/2 hours long, there will be time for questions and answers after the class. 

More Information: http://www.keepcalmandcarry.net/utah-cfp-oregon-chl-concealed-carry-class-1-9-2014-Schedule

I have a WWI era, dated 1918, U.S. Rifle, cal .30 Model of 1917 to offer up in trade for a brace of Ruger Vaqueros in .357.  This US battle rifle has much of its original finish left and the patina that you would expect from an original piece of American History.  I will include a 1917 Bayonet with the rifle as well (no scabbard).  The stock is correct but at sometime in the last 96 years it was lightly refinished.  The bore if just fine with great rifling, it shoots perfectly, is accurate with a smooth action.  I am not a historian or collector but I do know original historical guns like this will only appreciate in value over the years.

I am looking for a pair of Ruger Vaqueros in .357, 5.5" barrels, I prefer unmodified guns and it does not matter if blued or stainless and, it would be a plus if you had leather to go with them.  I will also add in some quality mil-surp ammo if you will provide ammo too.

I am in Ft. Collins and can meet in the Loveland to Ft. Collins area for transfer.  I will pay my transfer and BGC fees but since my rifle qualifies as C&R there are no fees for you to take possession.  I value this rifle with the bayonet at $1000 +/- 

I am already have second thoughts so act quick before I change my mind.  This will be the only bump and if no action in the next week I will keep it, enjoy shooting it and just look for the best price I can for what I want and pay cash.

Our course exceeds all firearms safety training exceeds the requirements to obtain your Utah CFP, pursuant to Utah Code Title 53 Chapter 5 Section 704, and your Oregon CHL pursuant to ORS 166.291(f)(G). 

Our process starts with issuing you a packet of information, an application for your permit, and fingerprint cards that you will need. We will do your fingerprinting, take your passport photo and make copies of your driver's license before class starts. You will also have all the information you need to obtain your Oregon CHL from your local Sheriff's department. 

Subjects covered are: Basic Handgun Safety, Tactical Issues, Concealed Carry Firearm selection tips, Ammunition, Holsters, Gun Free Zones, Reciprocity, Cleaning, Storage, Firearm Transport, Justifiable Force, Criminal and Civil liability, How to interact with Law Enforcement, and how to apply for your Permit. 

After attending this class you will have a fundamental understanding about handgun safety and the rights and responsibilities and laws associated with the carrying of a concealed Handgun in multiple states. 

This is NOT a live firing class. Do NOT bring a firearm with you to the class. 

Even though the class time is only scheduled to be 2 1/2 hours long, there will be time for questions and answers after the class.

Do your homework before you just dismiss this pistol for being a Brazilian made gun. Beretta built a lot of fame with its model 92 (M9) and when the cards fell just right they sold their South American plant with all the tools and worker. They sold it to Taurus who continued to produce the guns with Beretta's actual machinery. These are facts, not conjecture. The only virtual differences are in favor of the Taurus belive it of not. Beretta uses plastic guide rods and other parts, the Taurus counterpart features ALL STEEL PARTS. MANY EVEN GO SO FAR AS TO RATE THE TAURUS AS BETTER THAN THE BERETTA. From Dillon:

Makes short work out of trimming large quantities of rifle brass.
The RT 1200B is used just like a standard size die. The big difference is that while you are pushing the case into the die to size it, a 1/4 horsepower electric motor driving a carbide cutter is trimming the case to length. Chips are drawn off through a vacuum manifold that clamps to the outside of the special size/trim die. (Vacuum cleaner and hose not included.) Outside diameter of manifold as 1.250"
The RT1200B is equipped with a quick-disconnect power cord; and it can be used on any standard reloader, single stage or progressive.
